               <msContents>
                  <summary>The second of two volumes of the <title>Ḥabīb al-Siyar</title> (Beloved
                     of Biographies), uniformly bound with <ref
                        target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_7322"><idno>Persian MS
                           815</idno></ref>. Originally completed by the author <persName
                        key="person_45109504" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/45109504/"
                        xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" type="standard">Ghiyās̲ al-Dīn ibn Humām al-Dīn (ca.
                        1475–1535)</persName> known as <addName key="person_45109504"
                        ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/45109504/">Khvāndamīr (1487–1524 CE)</addName>,
                     in <date>937 AH (1530–31 CE)</date>, a maternal grandson of Timurid-era
                     historian <persName role="asn" key="person_175393012"
                        ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/175393012">Mīrkhvānd (1433–1498)</persName>. He
                     presents a general history spanning the pre-Islamic period until the reign of
                     Shāh Ismāʿīl I, which dedicates to then-governor of Herat, <persName role="dte"
                        key="person_f7917">Karīm al-Din Khvājah Ḥabīb-Allāh Sāvajī (fl. early-mid
                        16th c.)</persName>, hence the title. The entire work consists of a preface,
                     an introduction, followed by three volumes, containing four sections each
                     appended with lists of names of prominent figures associated with specific
                     periods, followed by an epilogue. While unsigned and undated, <date
                        calendar="#Gregorian" notBefore="1700" notAfter="1744">mid-18th
                        century</date> notations and seal impressions within the volume suggest it
                     dates to earlier that century, and comes from the <placeName
                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208" key="place_7000208">Indian
                        subcontinent</placeName>. </summary>
